segments.text: More recently, in Ohio, first of all, during the Vietnam War, we were always in there, but we were always arguing electoral politics, and we were always combining the fight for the right to dissent along with the fight against the Vietnam War.
The conclusion of all those things, I just had
breakfast two mornings ago with Sid Pack.
Dr. Sid Pack was one of the organizers of the big mobilization against the Vietnam War in Washington.
I'd known him when he was at Milwaukee Downer College and organized the Committee of 100 in Milwaukee against UI.
Then the peace came and Sid leaves
He's a professor of sociology at Clark College somewhere in Massachusetts.
Worcester, I think.
Worcester, right.
So we're seeing each other for the first time in fifteen years.
We're talking about this whole change.
We never lost track of each other.
It's just that he's one case where we never really got him to keep the question of dissent
upper-most of his mind, and it doesn't relate to the peace movement.
Sid is just recovering from a horrible violation of his academic freedom rights from a student that accused him of sexual harassment at Clark College.
He's just fought two years, he's $100,000 in debt, trying to fight back to get his tenured position again, having won, and the student totally
discredited, and the faculty leader that tried to fire Sid committing suicide.
Horrible thing.
My goodness.
Anyway, Sid is now back, finally.
But it was his own little lesson on civil liberties, I think, partly involved.
I want to get you to the classical example.
The best coalition building between all the movements of the 60s
and 70s, and I think should be even now, is the American Friends Service Committee in Northeastern Ohio.
The guy out there, John Looney, used to be a business person.
How do you spell his last name?
L-O-O-N-E-Y.
He's the Northeastern Ohio director of the American Friends Service Committee.
Four years ago, as the Reagan dangers for peace developed,
He began a series of three conferences in Cleveland, Akron, Youngstown, called Guns or Butter?
One, Guns or Butter?
Two, Guns or Butter?
Three.
Obvious expression of, you know, that issue of the, do we put our money into feeding people or into war?
At each of these conferences,
John Looney invited me to speak on the right to dissent, the right to dissent for peace.

The classical example was two years ago at Trinity Cathedral in downtown Cleveland, a beautiful Gothic Episcopalian cathedral where the main thing held, among the other things that the AFSC and Looney did, is they recognized that people don't drive 35 miles for a meeting.
So each of these conferences were held simultaneously in Youngstown, Akron, and Cleveland, three separate conferences, and the speakers rotated.
You'd speak in the morning in Youngstown, noon in Akron, the evening at Cleveland.
So I'm speaking with Julian Bond and Marian Anderson at the beautiful, jam-packed cathedral, Episcopal Church,
Trinity Cathedral in Cleveland.
Marian Anderson from Flint, Michigan, I think, had spoken on the economic cost of nuclear war.
She's the authority.
She presented factual data showing that for every nuclear warhead built, the same amount of money put into domestic work could have produced 5,000
new domestic jobs in Northeastern Ohio.
Very telling argument there.
Twelve, fifteen percent unemployment there.
Then Julian spoke, and his argument was that for every dollar we pay in taxes, that fifty-seven cents on the dollar goes to pay for past or future wars.
I was to be the third speaker on the right of dissent for peace.
As I am about, Julia's is down, I'm walking up this marble, it's a huge cathedral, a big marble podium that you, up where the priest stands to speak.
Huge thing.
I'm up there.
A woman at the far end of the cathedral stands up, no microphones, no nothing, and just hollers out, top of her voice, that,

Senator Bond, everybody turns around to see what it was, she said, after what you and Marian Anderson have just said, I say, when tax day comes, let none of us pay 57 cents on a dollar for taxes, you know, for the war.
And then, the lady, by the way, was a stereotype of a very middle-class bourgeois lady.
She was
tailored, tall, trim, flowery hat, and the accent, her accent was just the stereotype of what I think of as a high, high, high Episcopalian, the nearest thing there is to God, you know.
Well, Julian, this woman then said, are you with me?
She turned to the audience and walks up the aisle, cheering both sides of the nave, just the church roaring with cheering for her.
Julian Bond finally gets the floor back.
He says, my good lady, let me steal one on Frank.
What you have just said is an advocacy of criminal conduct.
Namely, don't pay taxes.
As a result, the FBI and CIA agents who are legally in this cathedral tonight due to President Reagan's
new guidelines from the CIA and the FBI, have taken due note of what you have said.
And now we'll begin an investigation of you personally and the Social Action Committee of your church.
Well, it's dead silence.
What an introduction for you.
Dead silence.
But
probably seemed like thirty seconds, about ten seconds.

What Julian had done, and was carried across, and this would never have happened without the coalition building that they knew there in Cleveland, is that Julian had made the point of the indivisibility of the struggle for peace with the struggle for civil liberties.
It's a long, long theory.
I best answer questions like that by telling you.
I think that lesson of Wisp in 1962, and this thing from Julian and Marian Anderson in 1980, are the way we try to work.

Always arguing that peace is indivisible, with civil rights are indivisible, with tying things together that we must have one coalition, and no matter what your social concern may be, you've got to include within that the civil liberties component.
And that's a place where we have to stop now because
